site. Jackpot. Seventeen Lancaster-Lebanon League pigskin standouts on Friday earned PA Football Writers All-State honors in Class 4A, 5A and 6A. The hefty list includes seven players in 4A, six players in 5A, and another four standouts in 6A. The 4A honorees: Elco RB Jake Williams, Twin Valley TE Ean Winchester and Raiders' O-line road-grader Paul McClune, and four players from Manheim Central, including QB Zac Hahn, WR Aaron Enterline, DB Bode Sipel and RB Brycen Armold, who was selected as an athlete. The 5A honorees: Cocalico two-way warrior Aaryn Longenecker was named as an athlete; Garden Spot dual-threat QB Kye Harting was tabbed as an athlete; Exeter RB Jayden Zandier; and three players from Ephrata, including QB Sam McCracken, who was slotted in as an athlete, plus LB Quintin Pfautz and DB Jeremiah Knowles. The 6A honorees: Three standouts from Manheim Township, including QB Hayden Johnson, WR Landon Kennel and DE Eli Rodriguez were named, plus Wilson QB Tommy Hunsicker, who was tabbed as an athlete. Players were nominated — and then voted upon — by football writers from across the state. The local big-school honorees joined L-L League brethren Cael Harter from Annville-Cleona, Elijah Cunningham from Lancaster Catholic, Mason Semmel from Hamburg, and Wyomissing’s Caleb Brewer and Ryker Jones, who earned small-school honors earlier this week. In all, the L-L League produced 22 prestigious PA Football Writers All-State players from the 2023 season. Hahn passed for 2,870 yards with 39 TD strikes; Enterline had 80 catches for 1,508 yards with 25 TD grabs — all tops in the league; Armold rushed for 1,686 yards with 23 TD gallops; Sipel registered 85 tackles with a pair of sacks; Williams paced the league with 2,401 rushing yards and 30 TD runs; and Winchester had 16 receptions and added 11 TD runs, thanks in large part to the blocking of McClune up front. Harting passed for 1,899 yards with 33 TD tosses, and he rushed for 1,170 yards with 12 TD keepers, becoming just the third player in league history with back-to-back 1,000-pass/1,000-rush seasons; Longenecker rushed for 1,312 yards with 16 TD runs, piled up 2,069 all-purpose yards and had five interceptions; Zandier scooted for 1,358 yards with 15 TD runs; McCracken passed for 2,530 yards with 25 TD flips; Pfautz piled up 173 tackles with three interceptions; and Knowles had 151 tackles with three picks. Johnson threw for 2,896 yards with 49 TD throws against zero interceptions, and finished his career as the fourth-leading passer in league history; Kennel had 64 catches for 1,119 yards with 25 TD grabs; Rodriguez amassed 70 tackles with seven sacks; and Hunsicker passed for 2,180 yards with 24 TD strikes. 2023 PFW 4A ALL-STATE TEAM Co-Players of the Year: Tiqwai Hayes, Aliquippa; Stone 'Need to Sell? Click here to place a classified ad. Support Local Journalism & receive Diamond Card discounts! Best of Photo Gallery! Watch #OnTheStacks podcast! New episode every Wednesday. Juneteenth National Independence Day, known more simply as just Juneteenth, is officially on Wednesday, June 19. But the weekend before is as good a time as any to get the celebration started. WILKES-BARRE TWP. — After years of speculation and anticipation, the dream of many devout convenience store customers is about to come true. The Garden Drive-In hosted its inaugural Picklefest on Saturday afternoon, bringing together vendors and locals for a celebration of all things related to pickles. Wyoming Area held its 58th commencement on Friday night at Jake Sobeski Stadium. 156 students graduated. For a full story and additional photos, look for the Times Leader’s special graduation section later this month. The final day of the Osterhout Free Library’s 47th Annual Tent Book Sale is Saturday. Offering a variety of reading options, the book sale has been open to the public for free since June 8. WILKES-BARRE — As George M. Cohan’s song goes, “it’s a grand old flag,” and today is the day we celebrate it. Due to outstanding questions, a Luzerne County Council majority chose not to vote Thursday on a $500,000 American Rescue Plan Act allocation for the county fair’s nonprofit overseer to repair flood damage at its Dallas fairground. The Greater Wyoming Valley Chamber of Commerce held, for the second time, its Light Up the Valley event on Public Square in Wilkes-Barre. There, they handed out Change Maker awards to over 40 people. DALLAS — There were two options for the Dallas Mavericks. Pack for Boston, or pack for vacation. Gerrit Cole looks more than ready to start facing major league hitters. PINEHURST, N.C. — The U.S. Open is a new experience for Ludvig Aberg, not that anyone would notice the way his machine-like game gave him the 36-hole lead Friday. PINEHURST, N.C. — Tiger Woods was unable to find the right mix of quality shots and timely breaks at Pinehurst No. 2 to extend his first U.S. Open appearance in four years into the weekend. EDMONTON, Alberta — One win away from a championship, it feels like the Florida Panthers are treating Game 4 of the Stanley Cup Final like Game 44 of the regular season. NEWTON, Iowa — Martin Truex Jr. announced Friday he will retire from full-time racing at the end of the season, saying it was time to live by his own schedule after 19 years in NASCAR’s Cup Series. Longtime Wilkes men’s basketball coach Jerry Rickrode has been selected to join the 2024 class of the Middle Atlantic Conference (MAC) Hall of Fame, according to a release issued by the university on Friday. EDMONTON, Alberta — Aleksander Barkov led the way offensively, Sergei Bobrovsky was in peak form in goal once again and the Florida Panthers are on the verge of lifting the Stanley Cup. Most obituaries published in the Reading Eagle are submitted through funeral homes and cremation services, but we will accept submissions from families. Obituaries can be emailed to obituaries@readingeagle.com. In addition to the text of the obituary, any photographs that you wish to include can be attached to this email. Please put the text of the obituary in a Word document, a Google document or in the body of the email. The Reading Eagle also requires a way to verify the death, so please include either the phone number of the funeral home or cremation service that is in charge of the deceased's care or a photo of his/her death certificate. We also request that your full name, phone number and address are all included in this email. All payments by families must be made with a credit card. We will send a proof of the completed obituary before we require payment. The obituary cannot run, however, until we receive payment in full. Obituaries can be submitted for any future date, but they must be received no later than 3:00 p.m. the day prior to its running for it to be published.
